You can achieve this by using JavaScript to validate the form input before submitting the data. I'll provide you with an example code snippet.

Assuming you have a form like this:

```html
<form id="eventForm">
  <label for="location">Location:</label>
  <input type="text" id="location" name="location" required>

  <label for="beginningDateTime">Beginning Date Time:</label>
  <input type="datetime-local" id="beginningDateTime" name="beginningDateTime" required>

  <input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>
<div id="errorMessage" style="color: red;"></div>
```

Add this JavaScript code to perform the validation:

```html
<script>
  const eventForm = document.getElementById('eventForm');
  const errorMessage = document.getElementById('errorMessage');

  // A sample data structure to store existing events (replace with actual data)
  const existingEvents = [
    { location: 'Conference Room', beginningDateTime: '2022-01-01T10:00' },
    { location: 'Meeting Room', beginningDateTime: '2022-01-02T14:00' },
  ];

  eventForm.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    const location = document.getElementById('location').value;
    const beginningDateTime = document.getElementById('beginningDateTime').value;

    if (isDuplicate(location, beginningDateTime)) {
      errorMessage.textContent = 'Error: Duplicate location and beginning date time found.';
    } else {
      errorMessage.textContent = '';
      // Submit the form data, e.g., to a server
      console.log('Submitting form data:', { location, beginningDateTime });
    }
  });

  function isDuplicate(location, beginningDateTime) {
    return existingEvents.some(
      (event) => event.location === location && event.beginningDateTime === beginningDateTime
    );
  }
</script>
```

This code checks the entered location and beginning date time against the existing events data (in `existingEvents` array) to see if there is a duplicate. If a duplicate is found, it displays an error message and prevents the form from being submitted. Replace the `existingEvents` array with your actual data source.

Note: In a real application, it's also a good idea to perform similar checks on the server-side, as client-side JavaScript can be bypassed.

Here's the TypeScript version of the code to check for duplicate events with the same location and beginning date time:

```typescript
interface Event {
  location: string;
  beginningDateTime: string;
}

// A sample data structure to store existing events (replace with actual data)
const existingEvents: Event[] = [
  { location: 'Conference Room', beginningDateTime: '2022-01-01T10:00' },
  { location: 'Meeting Room', beginningDateTime: '2022-01-02T14:00' },
];

function isDuplicate(location: string, beginningDateTime: string): boolean {
  return existingEvents.some(
    (event) => event.location === location && event.beginningDateTime === beginningDateTime
  );
}

// Usage example
const location = 'Conference Room';
const beginningDateTime = '2022-01-01T10:00';

if (isDuplicate(location, beginningDateTime)) {
  console.log('Error: Duplicate location and beginning date time found.');
} else {
  // Submit the form data, e.g., to a server
  console.log('Submitting form data:', { location, beginningDateTime });
}
```

This TypeScript code defines an `Event` interface and an `existingEvents` array to store existing events. The `isDuplicate` function checks if the given location and beginning date time match any of the existing events. Replace the `existingEvents` array with your actual data source.

Remember to integrate this TypeScript code into your application and transpile it to JavaScript before using it in a web page.
